english:
  title: On Ahn Gyeon's Ink Painting Scroll Owned by Guk-i
  author: Kim Jong-jik
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Who among Eastern masters paints mountains supreme?
    Since Yi Nyeong, none have matched his skill.
    Yet in your small scroll the mists arise,
    And I perceive at last that Ahn Gyeon touched true enlightenment.

    Distant peaks crowd together, stone on stone,
    While nearer mountains cradle rolling hills.
    Wild streams emerge from forest depths in ribbons,
    Winding gently where the village nestles in its curve.

    A traveler guides his weary donkey over the stone bridge,
    While fishermen pole their boats along the cliff-bound shore.
    Beneath the pines, modest thatched roofs flicker half-concealed—
    As if the hermits Shao Fu and Xu You called to each other there.

    Such stillness, such seclusion in the human realm—
    It seems the mists of Ruoye and Yunmen themselves have migrated here.
    The Three Han's rare beauty flows through every brushstroke;
    Why journey far when such perfection lies within reach?

    Do you not see how those who toil without rest—
    Like the old masters who could not return for ten long years—
    Have lost even the hearing to perceive what matters most?
  footnotes:
    - Yi Nyeong (李寧) refers to a legendary painter from ancient China, representing the classical ideal of landscape painting.
    - Shao Fu (巢父) and Xu You (許由) were legendary Chinese hermits who exemplified virtuous withdrawal from the world.
    - Ruoye (若耶) and Yunmen (雲門) are poetic place names associated with mist-shrouded landscapes and spiritual refinement.
    - The 'Three Han' (三韓) is a classical reference to Korea, here suggesting that Korean landscapes rival the great traditions of China.
    - The final lines likely reference court painters who devoted their lives to their art without achieving true spiritual attainment.
